  "plain_language_assessment": "M5q found the boundary clearly: once the CUDA context and persistent arena are already warm, the full 3546-fixture pre-divergence batch is modestly faster than CPU (0.300236 ms vs 0.324878 ms, 1.082x). But real Flye currently launches a fresh worker, so setup dominates: the same full batch is about 249.07 ms as a single persistent-bulk invocation and 268.81 ms in cold per-run allocation, versus 0.402 ms CPU. The win is real but trapped behind process/context setup; the next ROI target is a long-lived Flye-side read-alignment worker/session or equivalent context reuse before claiming integration speedup.",
